"Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now; they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations." Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are being relocated to the forward operating base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our mission is to support the ongoing siege and the subsequent attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a base camp at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Move out to your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into its respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed onto the tanks by the corporals. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his legs swing while he adjusted his backpack and the radio, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" Nemic asked after they had settled in.
"Are you talking about the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they let the animal go from a farmhouse. "Yeah, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small rooster searching the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
"Yes, he's still with him," Cohren replied as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks move out," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the column of tanks and Strykers roared to life as they began to move. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding on, shook as the brakes were released and they integrated into the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Although the swamp areas had frozen and the forests were snow-covered due to the winter storms, the mud was still ever-present.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whose name Cohren knew was Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought the matter would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated them."
"Underestimating them is a huge understatement," Nemic interjected. "We weren't prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the sheer number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly by the side of the Federation," said Orson defiantly. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"That's what you say now. But I've seen most eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot," explained Craith.
"We'll see about that," said Cohren, laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're picking up heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed up onto the tank and put on his specialty goggles. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," replied Cohren over his throat microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't recognize them," replied Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said, "Exodus Company, hold fire until under fire. Lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. When they came even closer, one of them hurried off to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, taking up firing positions.
"Enemy contact!" Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hill. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket raced past and struck behind the formation, hitting the ground, exploding, and scattering debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another struck sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition went off in the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 meters. Open fire," shouted the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew toward the hill and exploded, hurling mud and rock into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," shouted Knoxx, who was observing the hill with binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they began sprinting. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" asked Craith, as they watched.
"It looks like a capture," speculated Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared into the cloud of ash and smoke. Screams and gunshots echoed from the hill but quickly faded. Shortly after, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left marks in the ground. After they had returned to the cover of the convoy, they threw the figure to the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the figure, who was just trying to get up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the Sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get rid of this guy!"
